<!--
	Guided Lecture Notes worksheet: "Piecewise Forcing"
	Book sections (Exploring Differential Equations, geoff-cox/debookrs):
		c12-ltp/sec-unit-step-functions.ptx
		c12-ltp/sec-piecewise-functions.ptx
		c12-ltp/sec-piecewise-transform-rules.ptx
		c12-ltp/sec-transforming-piecewise-functions.ptx
		c12-ltp/sec-laplace-piecewise-method.ptx
	Old deck: source/notes/latex/ folder "06 lt"
	(05-Unit step Functions subfolders).
	Previous worksheet: ws-laplace-method.ptx; next: ws-linear-systems.

	Per the sourcing rules, every worked instance here is fresh: the
	canonical step-transform rules are shared reference facts, but no
	computed example (the step-form conversion, the forward/inverse
	instances, the IVP solve) appears in the book, the old deck, or
	earlier worksheets. Notation follows the book: u_c(t). Per the
	instructor overrides in CLAUDE.md section 4: no interactive content,
	and the whole topic stays on this one worksheet.

	Worksheet conventions: checklists/worksheet-conventions.md (see
	CLAUDE.md section 4 for this repo's parameters). In brief:
	  * Student/instructor split via component="stu" / component="key",
	    mirrored in structure; answers never live inside <fillin>.
	  * Worked problems: paired <exercise component="stu" workspace="Xin">
	    and <exercise component="key"> (statement + solution).
	  * True/False checks: one <exercise> + <solution component="key">.
	  * <page> = vertical print space, not topics; headings are
	    <p><term>...</term></p>; display math uses <md> (<me>/<men> are
	    prohibited here).
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-piecewise-forcing" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Piecewise Forcing</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li><p><term>Evaluate</term> the unit step function <m>u_c(t)</m> and use it to switch functions on at chosen times.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Rewrite</term> piecewise-defined forcing in step form.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Transform</term> step functions and delayed functions: <m>\mathcal{L}\{u_c(t)\} = \frac{e^{-cs}}{s}</m> and <m>\mathcal{L}\{f(t-c)\,u_c(t)\} = e^{-cs}F(s)</m>.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Invert</term> transforms containing <m>e^{-cs}</m> factors, reading the delay correctly.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Solve</term> an initial-value problem whose forcing switches on mid-story.</p></li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 1 : The unit step function; step form                            -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>The switch: forcing that turns on.</term></p>

		<p>
			Real systems get switched: a voltage applied at <m>t = 3</m>, a drug
			dose started at <m>t = 7</m>. The <term>unit step function</term>
			models the switch itself:
			<md>
				<mrow> u_c(t) = \begin{cases} 0 \amp t \lt c \\ 1 \amp t \ge c \end{cases} </mrow>
			</md>
			&#8212;worth <m>0</m> before time <m>c</m>, worth <m>1</m> from
			<m>c</m> onward. Multiplying any function by <m>u_c(t)</m> silences
			it before <m>c</m> and switches it on at <m>c</m>, which lets us
			rewrite piecewise formulas as single expressions.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						The function <m>u_c(t)</m> outputs <fillin characters="2"/> before
						time <m>c</m> and <fillin characters="2"/> afterward; the product
						<m>f(t)\,u_c(t)</m> is a copy of <m>f</m> that is switched
						<fillin characters="3"/> at <m>t = c</m>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						The function <m>u_c(t)</m> outputs <m>\underline{\textbf{0}}</m>
						before time <m>c</m> and <m>\underline{\textbf{1}}</m> afterward;
						the product <m>f(t)\,u_c(t)</m> is a copy of <m>f</m> that is
						switched <m>\underline{\textbf{on}}</m> at <m>t = c</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-tf-ramp">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p><m>u_c(t)</m> rises gradually from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m> near <m>t = c</m>.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False. The step is instantaneous&#8212;a jump discontinuity, not a
					ramp. That abruptness is the whole point (an ideal switch), and it
					is exactly the kind of forcing that undetermined coefficients
					could never touch but the Laplace transform handles cleanly.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-ex-stepform" component="stu" workspace="2.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					(a) Evaluate <m>u_7(3)</m>, <m>u_7(7)</m>, and <m>u_7(10)</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Write the piecewise forcing
					<md>
						<mrow> f(t) = \begin{cases} 3 \amp t \lt 7 \\ -1 \amp t \ge 7 \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
					in step form (a single expression using <m>u_7(t)</m>), and check
					your expression at <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 9</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-ex-stepform" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					(a) Evaluate <m>u_7(3)</m>, <m>u_7(7)</m>, and <m>u_7(10)</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Write the piecewise forcing
					<md>
						<mrow> f(t) = \begin{cases} 3 \amp t \lt 7 \\ -1 \amp t \ge 7 \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
					in step form (a single expression using <m>u_7(t)</m>), and check
					your expression at <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 9</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) <m>u_7(3) = 0</m> (before the switch), <m>u_7(7) = 1</m> (the
					switch is on at its own instant), <m>u_7(10) = 1</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Start at <m>3</m>; at <m>t = 7</m> the value must jump by
					<m>-1 - 3 = -4</m>, and a jump of size <m>k</m> at time <m>c</m> is
					<m>k\,u_c(t)</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> f(t) = 3 - 4\,u_7(t). </mrow>
					</md>
					Check: at <m>t = 0</m>, <m>3 - 4(0) = 3</m>; at <m>t = 9</m>,
					<m>3 - 4(1) = -1</m>. Start value plus (jump)&#215;(switch) is the
					recipe for any two-piece constant forcing.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 2 : Forward transform rules for steps                            -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Transforming switches and delays.</term></p>

		<p>
			Two rules carry the whole chapter (with
			<m>F(s) = \mathcal{L}\{f(t)\}</m>):
			<md>
				<mrow> \mathcal{L}\{u_c(t)\} = \frac{e^{-cs}}{s},
				       \qquad
				       \mathcal{L}\{f(t-c)\,u_c(t)\} = e^{-cs}\,F(s). </mrow>
			</md>
			The factor <m>e^{-cs}</m> is the <m>s</m>-domain fingerprint of a
			delay: <q>whatever happens, it happens <m>c</m> seconds late.</q>
			Note carefully that the second rule wants the <em>shifted</em>
			function <m>f(t-c)</m> riding the switch&#8212;not plain
			<m>f(t)</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						In the <m>s</m>-domain, an exponential factor <m>e^{-cs}</m>
						signals a <fillin characters="5"/> of length <m>c</m> in the
						<m>t</m>-domain; the delayed-function rule applies when the
						function multiplying <m>u_c(t)</m> is written in terms of
						<fillin characters="5"/>, not <m>t</m>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						In the <m>s</m>-domain, an exponential factor <m>e^{-cs}</m>
						signals a <m>\underline{\textbf{delay}}</m> of length <m>c</m> in
						the <m>t</m>-domain; the delayed-function rule applies when the
						function multiplying <m>u_c(t)</m> is written in terms of
						<m>\underline{\textbf{t-c}}</m>, not <m>t</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-ex-forward" component="stu" workspace="2.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Compute each transform:
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ \mathcal{L}\{u_7(t)\} \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ \mathcal{L}\{5\,u_8(t)\} \qquad
						       \text{(c)}\ \mathcal{L}\{(t-8)^3\,u_8(t)\}. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-ex-forward" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Compute each transform:
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ \mathcal{L}\{u_7(t)\} \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ \mathcal{L}\{5\,u_8(t)\} \qquad
						       \text{(c)}\ \mathcal{L}\{(t-8)^3\,u_8(t)\}. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) <m>\dfrac{e^{-7s}}{s}</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Linearity first: <m>5\,\mathcal{L}\{u_8(t)\} = \dfrac{5e^{-8s}}{s}</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) This fits the delayed-function rule perfectly: the function on
					the switch is already written in <m>t - 8</m>, with
					<m>f(t) = t^3</m> and <m>F(s) = \frac{3!}{s^4} = \frac{6}{s^4}</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> \mathcal{L}\{(t-8)^3\,u_8(t)\} = \frac{6\,e^{-8s}}{s^4}. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-tf-shift">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p><m>\mathcal{L}\{f(t)\,u_c(t)\} = e^{-cs}\,F(s)</m> for any function <m>f</m>.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False&#8212;the rule demands the <em>shifted</em> form
					<m>f(t-c)\,u_c(t)</m>. If the function on the switch is written in
					plain <m>t</m>, you must first rewrite it in terms of
					<m>t - c</m> (adding and subtracting <m>c</m> inside) before the
					rule applies. Skipping that rewrite is this chapter's most common
					error.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 3 : Inverting delays                                             -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Inverting a delay: read the fingerprint.</term></p>

		<p>
			Going backwards, the recipe is: peel off the <m>e^{-cs}</m>, invert
			what remains to get <m>f(t)</m>, then reattach the delay&#8212;every
			<m>t</m> becomes <m>t - c</m>, and the whole thing rides
			<m>u_c(t)</m>:
			<md>
				<mrow> \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{e^{-cs}\,F(s)\right\} = f(t-c)\,u_c(t). </mrow>
			</md>
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						When <m>Y(s)</m> contains a factor <m>e^{-cs}</m>, the inverse
						transform gains a factor <m>u_c(t)</m> and every <m>t</m> in the
						un-delayed inverse is replaced by <fillin characters="5"/>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						When <m>Y(s)</m> contains a factor <m>e^{-cs}</m>, the inverse
						transform gains a factor <m>u_c(t)</m> and every <m>t</m> in the
						un-delayed inverse is replaced by
						<m>\underline{\textbf{t-c}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-ex-inverse" component="stu" workspace="3.0in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Invert each transform, and for (b) describe the resulting function
					in words:
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{e^{-6s}}{s-2}\right\} \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1 - e^{-5s}}{s^2}\right\}. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-ex-inverse" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Invert each transform, and for (b) describe the resulting function
					in words:
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{e^{-6s}}{s-2}\right\} \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1 - e^{-5s}}{s^2}\right\}. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Without the delay, <m>\frac{1}{s-2}</m> inverts to
					<m>e^{2t}</m>; reattaching the <m>c = 6</m> delay:
					<md>
						<mrow> e^{2(t-6)}\,u_6(t). </mrow>
					</md>
					The exponent shifts too&#8212;<m>e^{2(t-6)}</m>, not
					<m>e^{2t}</m>: the growth starts fresh at the switch.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Split by linearity:
					<m>\frac{1}{s^2}</m> inverts to <m>t</m>, and
					<m>\frac{e^{-5s}}{s^2}</m> inverts to <m>(t-5)\,u_5(t)</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> y(t) = t - (t-5)\,u_5(t) = \begin{cases} t \amp t \lt 5 \\ 5 \amp t \ge 5 \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
					&#8212;a ramp that climbs steadily and then freezes at height
					<m>5</m>: the delayed ramp arrives and exactly cancels the
					climb.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 4 : Solving an IVP with switched forcing                         -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>The full method with a switch.</term></p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-ex-solve" component="stu" workspace="3.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A system is at rest until a constant input of strength <m>4</m>
					switches on at <m>t = 3</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> y' + 2y = 4\,u_3(t), \qquad y(0) = 0. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Solve with the Laplace method.
					(b) What is <m>y(t)</m> for <m>t \lt 3</m>? What value does
					<m>y</m> approach as <m>t \to \infty</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-ex-solve" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A system is at rest until a constant input of strength <m>4</m>
					switches on at <m>t = 3</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> y' + 2y = 4\,u_3(t), \qquad y(0) = 0. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Solve with the Laplace method.
					(b) What is <m>y(t)</m> for <m>t \lt 3</m>? What value does
					<m>y</m> approach as <m>t \to \infty</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) <term>Forward:</term> with <m>y(0) = 0</m>,
					<md>
						<mrow> (s + 2)\,Y = \frac{4e^{-3s}}{s}
						       \quad\Rightarrow\quad
						       Y = e^{-3s}\cdot\frac{4}{s(s+2)}. </mrow>
					</md>
					<term>Prepare:</term> PFD of the un-delayed part:
					<m>\frac{4}{s(s+2)} = \frac{2}{s} - \frac{2}{s+2}</m>, which
					inverts to <m>g(t) = 2 - 2e^{-2t}</m>.
					<term>Invert with the delay:</term>
					<md>
						<mrow> y(t) = g(t-3)\,u_3(t) = \left(2 - 2e^{-2(t-3)}\right) u_3(t). </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) For <m>t \lt 3</m> the step is off and <m>y \equiv 0</m>: the
					system stays asleep until the switch. Once on, the solution rises
					from <m>0</m> and levels off at <m>2</m> as
					<m>t \to \infty</m>&#8212;the same equilibrium a phase line for
					<m>y' = 4 - 2y</m> would predict, just delayed three seconds. Every
					tool in the course is visible in this one answer.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-pf-tf-asleep">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>If <m>y(0) = 0</m> and the forcing does not switch on until <m>t = c</m>, then the solution is identically zero for all <m>t \lt c</m>.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					True. Before the switch, the equation is homogeneous with zero
					initial state, and zero satisfies it perfectly&#8212;nothing pushes,
					so nothing moves. The step form makes this visible in the answer
					itself: every term of the response rides a <m>u_c(t)</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<title>Looking ahead</title>
			<p>
				With switches in hand, the Laplace story is told: transform, solve,
				invert&#8212;whatever the forcing throws at us. The final two
				worksheets change the cast instead of the forcing: <em>systems</em>
				of differential equations, where two or more unknowns&#8212;predator
				and prey, two coupled tanks&#8212;evolve together.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>
</worksheet>
